> Using pointers also means that clients of the library will need to perform their own nil checks where appropriate to prevent panics.<p>In practice, as your Rust comment alludes, I find working with nil properties in Go types (used to shuffle between the DB and JSON) to be quite painful. I end up keeping track of a lot more state than I really want to, and errors can be introduced subtly.<p>In Go, you can usually use a type&#x27;s zero value without doing anything special. But if that type contains any nil properties, you can&#x27;t presume this anymore. If I have:<p><pre><code>    type Thing struct {
        ID int
        Bad *string
    }
</code></pre>
I then have to do nil checks in every method that might handle Thing, or I have to make it accessible only via functions which perform those checks for me in advance. Either way, much less convenient.
